<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-567-625  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 567 625.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  Dec 1990 p29(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The potential of CIM for production plans. (computer-integratedmanufacturing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harris, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A recent study shows that the major factor in difficulties inimplementing CIM is conflict among functional groups arising fromtechnological and organizational factors.andP;  Production planning isa key use of computer-integrated manufacturing (CIM).andP;  A majorstep in developing CIM is the efficient design of the data base,since the data base is the heart of the production planningsystem.andP;  A company-wide approach to production planning will yieldthe greatest benefits; managers should not develop databases inisolation.andP;  Production planning involves information aboutcustomers, the inventory, materials and parts required, the timescale of production, operator, machine, and plant availability,and invoicing.andP;  A data base of all customers is essential.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Integrated ManufacturingBusiness PlanningData Base DesignFactory ManagementProduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>